1. Server is Slow
>> Problem could be CPU? Memory? Load?
>> cmds : 
top
htop
free -m
uptime
>> start by checking system load using top and uptime. 
Then I’d analyze CPU and memory usage to identify any resource-heavy processes

2. Disk is full
>> Situation 
>> Problem could be Which Parition? Which folder?
>> cmds :
df -h
du -sh
du -ah / | sort -rh | head -10
>> check disk usage using df -h, then identify large directories using du, and clean up logs or unnecessary files.

3. Application not accessible
>> Problem could be is service running? Port Open?
>> cmds :
ps aux | grep nginx
systemctl status nginx
ss -tulnp
curl localhost:80
>>verify if the service is running, check port availability, and test locally using curl to isolate the issue.

4. Logs showing errors
>> What errors? When started?
>> cmds
tail -f /var/log/app.log
grep ERROR /var/log/app.log
journalctl -u nginx
>> monitor logs using tail -f and filter errors using grep to identify the root cause.

5. High CPU usage 
>> Which processess?
>> cmds
top
ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head
kill -9 <pid>
identify the process consuming high CPU using top, then decide whether to optimize or terminate it.

6. Port already in use
>> cmds
lsof -i :8080
kill -9 <pid>
>> check which process is using the port and either stop it or reconfigure the application.

10. Permission denied error
>> cmds
ls -l
chmod 755 file.sh
chown user:user file.sh
>> check file permissions and ownership, then correct them using chmod or chown

11. Service fails after reboot
>> Auto-start? Config issue?
>> cmds
systemctl status nginx
systemctl enable nginx
journalctl -xe
>> check service status and logs, and ensure it is enabled to start on boot.

12. Docker container keeps crashing
>> cmds
docker ps -a
docker logs <container>
docker inspect <container>
check container logs and inspect configuration to identify crash reasons such as misconfiguration or dependency issues.

13. Website works locally but not externally
>> Firewall? Security group? Binding?
>> cmds
curl localhost:8080
ss -tulnp
ufw status
>> verify the app locally, then check firewall rules, port binding, and external access configurations.

14. Disk full due to logs
>> cmds
du -sh /var/log/ (star)
truncate -s 0 /var/log/syslog
>> identify large log files and clear or rotate them to free space.

15. Sudden traffic spike, app down
>> Scaling? Load?
>> cmds
top
netstat -an | wc -l
>> analyze system load and connections, then scale infrastructure or apply load balancing

16. Memory leak in application
>> cmds
top
ps aux --sort=-%mem | head
>> monitor memory usage over time, identify leaking processes, and restart or fix the application.

17. CI/CD pipeline failing
>> Build Logs, Permissions? Dependencies?
>> cmds
cat build.log
docker logs <container>
analyze pipeline logs, identify failure stage, and debug issues like dependency or permission errors.

18. Production outage (no clear error)
>> Infra? App? Network?
>> Approach
top
df -h
journalctl
ss -tulnp
curl localhost
follow a structured approach: check system health, disk, logs, network, and application status to isolate the issue layer by layer.

19. Intermittent issue
>> Timings? Logs Correlation?
>> cmds
journalctl --since "10 minutes ago"
grep ERROR logs
>> correlate logs with timestamps and monitor patterns to identify intermittent failures.

The Structure
Understand problem
Check system health
Check logs
Identify root cause
Fix + prevent
